DECLARATION MERGING occurs when TypeScript encounters multiple declarations with the same name — it merges them into one:

```typescript
interface Window {
  myLibVersion: string; // added to the existing Window interface!
}

// Later in code:
declare global {
  interface Window {
    analytics: Analytics;
  }
}
```

Merging rules:
• INTERFACES can always be merged (same name = merged shape)
• NAMESPACES can be merged with each other, with classes, enums, or functions
• TYPE ALIASES cannot be merged (error if redeclared)
• CLASSES cannot be merged (error if redeclared in same scope)

This is the foundation of MODULE AUGMENTATION and extending third-party types.

MODULE AUGMENTATION lets you add types to an external module without modifying it:

```typescript
// augment.ts — must be a module (has at least one import/export)
import 'express'; // makes this file a module

declare module 'express' {
  interface Request {
    user?: AuthenticatedUser; // adds user to Express's Request type
  }
}
```

This is how you:
• Add `req.user` to Express Request in typed middleware
• Add custom properties to Vue/React component instances
• Extend library types without forking them

Key requirement: the file must be a MODULE (have at least one `import` or `export`). If it has none, declarations are GLOBAL not augmentations.

For global augmentation use `declare global { ... }` inside a module.

.d.ts files (DECLARATION FILES) contain ONLY type information:

```typescript
// math.d.ts — no implementation, just types
export declare function add(a: number, b: number): number;
export declare const PI: number;
export declare interface Vector { x: number; y: number; }
```

They are used to:
• Type JavaScript libraries (DefinitelyTyped: `@types/xxx` packages)
• Provide types for code that was compiled or hand-written in JS
• Ship type definitions alongside library code

The `declare` keyword means 'this exists somewhere in JS — trust me'. Without it you'd need actual values.

You rarely write .d.ts files manually — TypeScript generates them when `declaration: true` is set in tsconfig. But understanding them is essential for library authors and working with legacy JS.

`paths` defines PATH ALIASES for TypeScript's module resolver:

```json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "baseUrl": ".",
    "paths": {
      "@app/*": ["src/app/*"],
      "@components/*": ["src/components/*"],
      "@utils": ["src/utils/index.ts"]
    }
  }
}
```

Now you can write:
```typescript
import { Button } from '@components/Button';
// instead of:
import { Button } from '../../../components/Button';
```

CRITICAL: `paths` is TypeScript-level only — it does NOT configure your bundler (webpack, Vite, esbuild). You must ALSO configure the bundler's alias to match. In Nx, this is done in `tsconfig.base.json` and synced to build tools.
